<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="551" pageId="18" pageNumber="547" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1803,1974]" lastBlockId="22.[151,1437,151,537]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="551" pageId="18" pageNumber="547">
The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hartmann" authorityYear="1954" box="[273,469,1839,1865]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="18" pageNumber="547" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[273,469,1839,1865]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="547">Microloxoconcha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
consists of 13 species, reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[892,959,1840,1866]" name="Japan" pageId="18" pageNumber="547">Japan</collectingCountry>
, Hawaii, 
<collectingCountry box="[1063,1158,1839,1865]" name="Ecuador" pageId="18" pageNumber="547">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1169,1273,1839,1865]" name="Tanzania" pageId="18" pageNumber="547">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
, the Black Sea and 
<collectingCountry box="[199,275,1876,1902]" name="France" pageId="18" pageNumber="547">France</collectingCountry>
(see summary in 
<bibRefCitation author="Tanaka, H. &amp; Ohtsuka, S." box="[476,755,1875,1901]" pageId="18" pageNumber="547" pagination="217 - 228" refId="ref15951" refString="Tanaka, H. &amp; Ohtsuka, S. (2019) Two new species of Microloxoconcha (Crustacea: Ostracoda) from the sublittoral zone in western Japan. Species Diversity, 24, 217 - 228. https: // doi. org / 10.12782 / specdiv. 24.217" type="journal article" year="2019">Tanaka &amp; Ohtsuka 2019</bibRefCitation>
). Eight are now known from 
<collectingCountry box="[1085,1152,1876,1902]" name="Japan" pageId="18" pageNumber="547">Japan</collectingCountry>
, but it is unclear if this is a result of a natural higher diversity of this taxon in 
<collectingCountry box="[746,813,1912,1938]" name="Japan" pageId="18" pageNumber="547">Japan</collectingCountry>
, or due to sampling bias. With the exception of 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith &amp; Chang, 2022" authorityName="Smith &amp; Chang" authorityYear="2022" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="18" pageNumber="547" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semicircularis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="547">Microloxoconcha semicircularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[457,548,1947,1973]" pageId="18" pageNumber="547">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[457,548,1947,1973]" pageId="18" pageNumber="547" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, species are from sublittoral (up to 
<quantity box="[958,1017,1947,1974]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2" pageId="18" pageNumber="547" unit="m" value="52.0">52 m</quantity>
depth) through to intertidal habitats, with seven of the species reported from beaches. Thus, 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith &amp; Chang, 2022" authorityName="Smith &amp; Chang" authorityYear="2022" box="[771,1133,151,177]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="22" pageNumber="551" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semicircularis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[771,1133,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="551">Microloxoconcha semicircularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1140,1230,151,177]" pageId="22" pageNumber="551">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1140,1230,151,177]" pageId="22" pageNumber="551" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is the first species of the genus to be found in low salinity brackish waters of a tidal part of a river, but as the sample was collected at low tide, at other times of the tidal cycle the salinity may be higher. 
<taxonomicName authority="Watanabe et al., 2008" authorityName="Watanabe" authorityYear="2008" box="[916,1436,223,249]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="22" pageNumber="551" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ikeyai">
<emphasis box="[916,1186,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="551">Microloxoconcha ikeyai</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Watanabe, S. &amp; Tsukagoshi, A. &amp; Higashi, R." box="[1193,1436,223,249]" pageId="22" pageNumber="551" pagination="53 - 71" refId="ref16149" refString="Watanabe, S., Tsukagoshi, A. &amp; Higashi, R. (2008) Taxonomy and ecology of two new interstitial cytheroid Ostracoda (Crustacea) from Shimoda, Central Japan. Species Diversity, 13, 53 - 71. https: // doi. org / 10.12782 / specdiv. 13.53" type="journal article" year="2008">
Watanabe 
<emphasis box="[1310,1373,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="551">et al.,</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
was collected from interstitial habitats with a range of 1–33‰ salinity (
<bibRefCitation author="Watanabe, S. &amp; Tsukagoshi, A. &amp; Higashi, R." box="[975,1221,259,285]" pageId="22" pageNumber="551" pagination="53 - 71" refId="ref16149" refString="Watanabe, S., Tsukagoshi, A. &amp; Higashi, R. (2008) Taxonomy and ecology of two new interstitial cytheroid Ostracoda (Crustacea) from Shimoda, Central Japan. Species Diversity, 13, 53 - 71. https: // doi. org / 10.12782 / specdiv. 13.53" type="journal article" year="2008">
Watanabe 
<emphasis box="[1094,1152,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="551">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
), and other marine interstitial ostracods demonstrate high tolerance to a wide range of salinities (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Tanaka, H. &amp; Tsukagoshi, A." box="[1050,1357,295,321]" pageId="22" pageNumber="551" pagination="39 - 57" refId="ref16002" refString="Tanaka, H. &amp; Tsukagoshi, A. (2010) Two new interstitial species of the genus Parapolycope (Crustacea: Ostracoda) from central Japan. Zootaxa, 2500 (1), 39 - 57. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2500.1.2" type="journal article" year="2010">Tanaka &amp; Tsukagoshi 2010</bibRefCitation>
). Thus, the presence of 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith &amp; Chang, 2022" authorityName="Smith &amp; Chang" authorityYear="2022" box="[329,692,331,357]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="22" pageNumber="551" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semicircularis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[329,692,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="551">Microloxoconcha semicircularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[700,790,331,357]" pageId="22" pageNumber="551">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[700,790,331,357]" pageId="22" pageNumber="551" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
from a tidal part of a river is not necessarily unexpected; other species may be found in similar habitats, and conversely, 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith &amp; Chang, 2022" authorityName="Smith &amp; Chang" authorityYear="2022" box="[879,1243,367,393]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cytheromatidae" genus="Microloxoconcha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="22" pageNumber="551" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semicircularis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[879,1243,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="551">Microloxoconcha semicircularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1252,1344,367,393]" pageId="22" pageNumber="551">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1252,1344,367,393]" pageId="22" pageNumber="551" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
may be found in other 
<typeStatus box="[320,379,403,429]" pageId="22" pageNumber="551">types</typeStatus>
of habitats. Although ostracods can be collected in habitats with wide-ranging salinities, it is often unknown if they are active throughout the tidal cycle (but see 
<bibRefCitation author="Tanaka, H. &amp; Tsukagoshi, A." box="[940,1258,439,465]" pageId="22" pageNumber="551" pagination="39 - 57" refId="ref16002" refString="Tanaka, H. &amp; Tsukagoshi, A. (2010) Two new interstitial species of the genus Parapolycope (Crustacea: Ostracoda) from central Japan. Zootaxa, 2500 (1), 39 - 57. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2500.1.2" type="journal article" year="2010">Tanaka &amp; Tsukagoshi 2010</bibRefCitation>
). A strategy for dealing with such variable conditions may be to close the carapace and wait until salinities become agreeable. Thus, tolerance could be attained via behavioural changes rather than physiological adaptations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
